# Racer Game Architecture

- Keep `apps/client`, `apps/server`, and `packages/shared` strictly separated by responsibility.
- Put transport contracts, shared constants, and framework-agnostic model types in `packages/shared`.
- Keep React and Three.js code out of `apps/server`.
- Keep simulation rules, lap logic, and funny-item behavior out of React components and socket handlers.
- Treat socket handlers as transport wiring only. Parse payloads, delegate work, and emit results.
- Prefer small files with one reason to change. Split early when UI, transport, and simulation concerns start mixing.
- Client code may predict visuals later, but the server remains the authority for race state, collisions, laps, and winners.
- When adding a new multiplayer feature, decide first whether it belongs to:
  - view/rendering
  - input capture
  - socket transport
  - simulation/domain logic
  - shared protocol
